text: hi everyone
here the internet's busiest music nerd
and it's time for a review of this new
the garden album horse poop on route 66.
weirdo punks wyatt and fletcher shears
aka the garden are back with their fifth
album to date and while it may be one of
their shortest releases thus far in
their catalog i think it's also one of
their punchiest and most impressive not
to downplay the garden's previous
efforts though while i haven't been a
big garden fan up until this point it's
not hard to see why their wild eclectic
and experimental punky genre fusions
would catch on and even still i've
remained curious with each new album
release because i never really know what
i'm gonna get whether we're talking
about the intro haunted house on zillow
which is a horror themed piece of punk
with spooky laughs grinding riffs as
well as very aggressive and loose
drumming plus all these lyrics about
buying a haunted house it lasts just
about a minute or so we also have the
extremely lo-fi acoustic number orange
county punk rock legend which is
repetitive sure but there is a dead
milkman cheekiness to the lyrics
describing an infamous local punk figure
there's also the kind of creepy closer
at the campfire with these constant
ghoulish laugh samples playing in the
background like some kind of broken
decorative goblin toy from spirit
halloween which is honestly kind of
annoying even if the song at the core of
the track is kind of cool as i think the
message about falling asleep by a
campfire making mention of tales does
make the entire record feel almost like
a nightmare with maybe some of the
tracks at least in the track list being
little stories or vignettes to be shared
by a campfire in a creepy setting some
of the eerie vibes continue on to other
tracks on this record too it's almost
like a miniature or partial theme
there's all the sinister riffs and
melodies on oc-93 we have more ghastly
giggles on the intro of the track too
and maddening lyrics touching down on
paranoia claustrophobia being let to
burn it's a disorienting dive into a
disturbed mindset propelled with a
vicious performance there's also the
much sweeter but equally dark chainsaw
the door which features a lot of pumping
beats and cute little indie guitar
melodies that sound like something from
an early strokes record and the lyrics
on this thing blatantly about seeing a
door chainsawing through it which given
some of the themes of this lp i can't
help but think of like in a slasher
flick context there's also the following
track squished face slick pig living in
a smoky city that's a tongue twister the
twisted riffs atmosphere and lyrics on
this one make it one of the most
tortured songs in the entire garden
discography almost sounds like something
off of an early swans record filth era
but maybe a bit quirkier given that it
is the garden but yeah the track overall
is raw and vile as hell there are other
interesting stylistic variations across
the tracklist too the noise punk of
puerto de limosina the distortion on
this one is so intense
not a whole lot is translating outside
of these grinding bass riffs and snares
it's so chaotic and deafening but the
rage fueling this track is something to
behold then the title track i found to
be one of the garden's most creatively
produced songs with its jazzy chords and
summary guitar loops and pumping bass
and cool rhythmic breakdowns a lot of
texture a lot of instrumentation a lot
of switches along the run time of this
track but still a coherent song
structure and that's what i'm really
happy to hear because often as
the garden has tried random things on a
variety of different tracks in the past
it's usually the song that ends up
suffering what else could i be but a
jester also continues the group's
interesting efforts into sequence beats
and electronics the verses on this track
are also packed with the shouted punk
style raps whose lyrics read sort of
like a chaotic nightmare there's not a
whole lot else to the record outside of
that as again it is a pretty short
release but still colorful varied
hard-hitting fun kind of an eclectic and
in-your-face shock to the system and
while there is a lot of aggression and
ferocity to all of it their
simultaneously quite a bit of cheekiness
and humor too to take the edge off i'm
feeling a light to decent seven on this
one tran position have you given this
album a listen did you love it did you
hate it what would you rate it you're
the best you're the best what should i
review next hit the like if you like
please subscribe and please don't cry
hit the bell as well over here next to
my head it's another video you can check
out hit that up or the link to subscribe
to the channel anthony fantano the
garden
forever
